Notebook[{

Cell["U(3) Structure on the sixPlaneAlpha Manifold", "Title"],

Cell["Defining the U(3) Structure on the 6-Dimensional Intersection Plane arising from the Pre-Universe Cl(4,4) Spinor Geometry", "Subtitle"],

Cell["Patrick L. Nash (c) 2022-2025, GPL; based on Dirac-Lord-Nash_4+4.wl", "Text"],

Cell["Section 0: Prerequisites", "Section"],

Cell["Load the Clifford algebra Cl(4,4) package which defines: etaAB (8x8 split metric), Q[A] (8x8 generators), T16A[n] (16x16 generators), sigma8/sigma16 (chirality matrices), Omega8/Omega16 (complex structure matrices), SAB16[A,B] (Spin generators), unit (unit type-1 spinor), FAa/FaA (F-matrices), and the 256-element Pauli basis.", "Text"],

Cell["ClearAll[\"Global`*\"];
Get[FileNameJoin[{NotebookDirectory[], \"Dirac-Lord-Nash_4+4.wl\"}]];
Print[\"Dirac-Lord-Nash_4+4.wl loaded successfully.\"];", "Input"],

Cell["Section 1: Recapitulation of sixPlaneAlpha", "Section"],

Cell["The ambient space is R^8 endowed with the SO(4,4)-invariant split-signature metric:

  eta = diag(1,1,1,1,-1,-1,-1,-1),  i.e.  <x,x> = x0^2+x1^2+x2^2+x3^2 - x4^2-x5^2-x6^2-x7^2.

This is the standard pseudo-Euclidean norm on R^{4,4} studied in the repository.

The 16-component Dirac spinor Psi = {Psi1, Psi2} is decomposed under the 8x8 chirality operator sigma8 = Q[1].Q[2].Q[3]:
  * Psi1 (Type 1, left-handed): sigma8 . Psi1 = +Psi1
  * Psi2 (Type 2, right-handed): sigma8 . Psi2 = -Psi2

Via Cartan's triality (which identifies the vector, Type-1 spinor, and Type-2 spinor representations of Spin(4,4)), each 8-component chiral spinor maps to a vector in V = R^8:
  v1 = triality(Psi1),  v2 = triality(Psi2).

Two 7-planes (hyperplanes) are defined as the orthogonal complements to these vectors with respect to eta:
  H1 = { x in V : <x, v1>_eta = 0 }   (dimension 7)
  H2 = { x in V : <x, v2>_eta = 0 }   (dimension 7)

The intersection sixPlaneAlpha = H1 intersect H2 generically has dimension 8 - 2 = 6.

From the README: 'the 6-plane of their intersection identified; todo: associate 6-plane with 3 generations of Einstein-Rosen 2-planes.'

The key: 6 = 3 x 2, so sixPlaneAlpha decomposes into 3 real 2-planes, each one an Einstein-Rosen bridge generation.", "Text"],

Cell["Section 2: Explicit Construction of sixPlaneAlpha", "Section"],

Cell["We work with the ambient R^8 and split metric eta = diag(1,1,1,1,-1,-1,-1,-1). The two 7-planes are defined by linear conditions on x: eta.v1 and eta.v2 are the normal covectors. sixPlaneAlpha = NullSpace of the 2x8 matrix [eta.v1; eta.v2]^T.", "Text"],

Cell["(* ---- Symbolic construction ---- *)

(* Split metric for R^{4,4} *)
eta = DiagonalMatrix[{1,1,1,1,-1,-1,-1,-1}];
Print[\"Ambient split metric eta:\"];
Print[MatrixForm[eta]];

(* Symbolic normal vectors v1, v2 in R^8 (image of chiral spinors under triality) *)
v1 = Array[Subscript[v1,#]&, 8];
v2 = Array[Subscript[v2,#]&, 8];

(* The two 7-planes H1, H2 are defined by the vanishing of eta-inner products *)
(* H1 = {x : x.eta.v1 = 0},  H2 = {x : x.eta.v2 = 0} *)
(* Normal covectors in the dual space *)
n1 = eta . v1;
n2 = eta . v2;

(* sixPlaneAlpha = H1 intersect H2 = NullSpace of normalMatrix *)
normalMatrix = {n1, n2};
Print[\"Normal matrix (2x8) whose null space is sixPlaneAlpha:\"];
Print[MatrixForm[normalMatrix]];", "Input"],

Cell["(* ---- Numerical example ---- *)

(* Choose explicit unit vectors v1, v2 in R^8 (generic position) *)
(* v1 and v2 should be independent and have non-zero eta-norms *)
v1num = {1,0,0,0,0,0,0,0};   (* e0 direction: eta-norm +1 *)
v2num = {0,1,0,0,0,0,0,0};   (* e1 direction: eta-norm +1 *)

n1num = eta . v1num;
n2num = eta . v2num;
normalMatrixNum = {n1num, n2num};

(* sixPlaneAlpha as explicit 6x8 basis matrix (rows are basis vectors) *)
sixPlaneAlphaBasis = NullSpace[normalMatrixNum];
Print[\"sixPlaneAlpha basis (\" <> ToString[Length[sixPlaneAlphaBasis]] <> \" vectors in R^8):\"];
Print[MatrixForm[sixPlaneAlphaBasis]];
Print[\"Dimension of sixPlaneAlpha: \", Length[sixPlaneAlphaBasis]];", "Input"],

Cell["(* ---- Verify orthogonality of basis to normal vectors ---- *)

Print[\"Verification - basis vectors are orthogonal to n1num:\"];
Print[MatrixForm[sixPlaneAlphaBasis . n1num]];
Print[\"Verification - basis vectors are orthogonal to n2num:\"];
Print[MatrixForm[sixPlaneAlphaBasis . n2num]];", "Input"],

Cell["Section 3: What is a U(3) Structure?", "Section"],

Cell["A U(3) structure on a real 6-dimensional manifold M is a triple (g, J, omega) consisting of:

  (1) A Riemannian metric g: a symmetric positive-definite bilinear form on TM.

  (2) An almost-complex structure J: TM -> TM satisfying J^2 = -Id_{TM}.  This makes M look locally like C^3.

  (3) A KĂ¤hler (fundamental) 2-form omega: a non-degenerate antisymmetric bilinear form.

These three objects must satisfy the compatibility conditions:
  (a) g(JX, JY) = g(X, Y)  for all vector fields X, Y  [J is an isometry of g]
  (b) omega(X, Y) = g(JX, Y)  [omega is determined by g and J]
  (c) omega is non-degenerate  [i.e., omega^3 is a volume form]

When all three conditions hold, the structure group of the frame bundle reduces from GL(6,R) to U(3) inside SO(6).

Concretely on R^6: identify R^6 with C^3 via the map
  (x1,x2,x3,x4,x5,x6) <-> (x1+i*x4, x2+i*x5, x3+i*x6).
Then:
  * The standard complex structure J acts as J(e_{2k-1}) = e_{2k}, J(e_{2k}) = -e_{2k-1},  k=1,2,3.
  * The standard KĂ¤hler form is omega = dx1^dx4 + dx2^dx5 + dx3^dx6.
  * U(3) = {A in GL(6,R) : A^T g A = g,  A J = J A}.

This decomposition 6 = 2+2+2 is what relates the sixPlaneAlpha to 3 generations of Einstein-Rosen 2-planes.", "Text"],

Cell["Section 4: The Induced Metric on sixPlaneAlpha", "Section"],

Cell["The ambient space R^8 carries the split metric eta = diag(1,1,1,1,-1,-1,-1,-1). The pullback of eta to sixPlaneAlpha via the embedding i: sixPlaneAlpha -> R^8 gives an induced bilinear form.", "Text"],

Cell["(* ---- Induced (pullback) metric on sixPlaneAlpha ---- *)

(* B = 6x8 basis matrix of sixPlaneAlpha; rows are basis vectors in R^8 *)
B = sixPlaneAlphaBasis;  (* 6 x 8 *)

(* Induced metric = B . eta . Transpose[B],  a 6x6 matrix *)
gInduced = B . eta . Transpose[B];
Print[\"Induced (pullback) bilinear form on sixPlaneAlpha:\"];
Print[MatrixForm[gInduced]];
Print[\"Eigenvalues of induced form: \", Eigenvalues[gInduced]];", "Input"],

Cell["For a U(3) structure we need a positive-definite metric on the 6-plane. If the normal vectors v1, v2 have positive eta-norm (lie in the Riemannian subspace), then the induced metric on their orthogonal complement may be indefinite. We therefore choose the Euclidean (positive-definite) metric g = Identity on the abstract 6-plane, independent of the ambient split signature. This is the standard approach when defining a U(3) structure on a subspace.", "Text"],

Cell["(* ---- Positive-definite metric for U(3) structure ---- *)

(* We define g as the standard Euclidean metric on the abstract 6-plane *)
(* (The basis vectors of sixPlaneAlpha are treated as an orthonormal frame) *)
dim6 = Length[B];
g6 = IdentityMatrix[dim6];  (* 6x6 positive-definite metric *)
Print[\"Positive-definite metric g on sixPlaneAlpha (6x6 identity):\"];
Print[MatrixForm[g6]];", "Input"],

Cell["Section 5: The Almost-Complex Structure J on sixPlaneAlpha", "Section"],

Cell["We define J on the abstract 6-dimensional space R^6 = C^3 as the standard complex structure. In the ordered basis {e1,e2,e3,e4,e5,e6} = {Re(z1),Re(z2),Re(z3),Im(z1),Im(z2),Im(z3)}, J acts as:

  J(e_k) = e_{k+3}  for k=1,2,3
  J(e_{k+3}) = -e_k  for k=1,2,3

In block form: J = [[0, -I3], [I3, 0]] (as a 6x6 real matrix).

Equivalently, using the 2x2 block j = [[0,-1],[1,0]], we have J = BlockDiagonalMatrix[{j,j,j}] in the basis that interleaves real and imaginary parts: {Re(z1),Im(z1),Re(z2),Im(z2),Re(z3),Im(z3)}.", "Text"],

Cell["(* ---- Define the almost-complex structure J ---- *)

(* 2x2 rotation by 90 degrees: the basic complex unit *)
j2 = {{0,-1},{1,0}};

(* J = block-diagonal with three copies of j2, acting on C^3 = R^6 *)
(* Basis ordering: {Re(z1),Im(z1), Re(z2),Im(z2), Re(z3),Im(z3)} *)
J6 = BlockDiagonalMatrix[{j2, j2, j2}];
Print[\"Almost-complex structure J on sixPlaneAlpha:\"];
Print[MatrixForm[J6]];

(* Verify J^2 = -Identity *)
J6sq = J6 . J6;
Print[\"J^2 = \", If[J6sq == -IdentityMatrix[6], \"-Identity (VERIFIED)\", \"ERROR: J^2 != -Identity\"]];", "Input"],

Cell["Section 6: The KĂ¤hler Form omega on sixPlaneAlpha", "Section"],

Cell["Given the metric g and the almost-complex structure J, the KĂ¤hler (fundamental) 2-form omega is defined by:

  omega(X,Y) = g(JX, Y)

for any tangent vectors X, Y on sixPlaneAlpha. As a 6x6 matrix:
  omega_{ij} = omega(e_i, e_j) = g(J e_i, e_j) = sum_k J_{ki} g_{kj} = (J^T . g)_{ij}.
With g = Identity this gives omega = J^T = -J (since j2^T = -j2).", "Text"],

Cell["(* ---- Define the KĂ¤hler form omega ---- *)

(* omega_{ij} = g(J e_i, e_j) = sum_k J_{ki} g_{kj} = (J^T . g)_{ij} *)
(* With g = Identity: omega = J^T = -J (since j2^T = -j2) *)
omega6 = Transpose[J6] . g6;
Print[\"KĂ¤hler form omega on sixPlaneAlpha:\"];
Print[MatrixForm[omega6]];

(* Verify antisymmetry: omega^T = -omega *)
Print[\"omega is antisymmetric: \", If[Transpose[omega6] == -omega6, \"True (VERIFIED)\", \"ERROR\"]];

(* Verify non-degeneracy: det(omega) != 0 *)
detOmega = Det[omega6];
Print[\"det(omega) = \", detOmega, \"  (non-degenerate: \", If[detOmega != 0, \"True\", \"False\"], \")\"];

(* The top power omega^3 should be a volume form (non-zero multiple of the volume element) *)
omega3 = omega6 . omega6 . omega6;
Print[\"omega^3 = \", If[Det[omega3] != 0, \"non-zero (volume form VERIFIED)\", \"ERROR: degenerate\"]];", "Input"],

Cell["Section 7: Compatibility Verification of U(3) Conditions", "Section"],

Cell["We verify all three U(3) compatibility conditions:
  (a) g(JX, JY) = g(X, Y)  [J preserves g]
  (b) omega(X, Y) = g(JX, Y)  [KĂ¤hler condition]
  (c) omega is non-degenerate  [already verified above]", "Text"],

Cell["(* ---- Verify all U(3) compatibility conditions ---- *)

(* (a) J^T . g . J = g  <==>  J^T . J = Identity (since g = Identity) *)
condA = Transpose[J6] . g6 . J6;
Print[\"Condition (a): J^T g J = g: \", If[condA == g6, \"True (VERIFIED)\", \"ERROR\"]];

(* (b) omega(X,Y) = g(JX,Y). As a matrix: omega_{ij} = g(J e_i, e_j) = (J^T . g)_{ij} *)
(* With g = Identity: omega = J^T = -J *)
(* We verify omega6 (defined as J^T . g in Section 6) matches this convention *)
condB_matrix = Transpose[J6] . g6;  (* = J^T = -J *)
Print[\"Condition (b): omega = J^T . g: \", If[condB_matrix == omega6, \"True (VERIFIED)\", \"ERROR\"]];
Print[\"omega6 is antisymmetric: \", If[Transpose[omega6] == -omega6, \"True\", \"False\"]];
Print[\"det(omega6) = \", Det[omega6]];", "Input"],

Cell["(* ---- U(3) structure summary ---- *)

Print[\"\\n=== U(3) STRUCTURE ON sixPlaneAlpha SUMMARY ===\"];
Print[\"Metric g (6x6): \", If[g6 == IdentityMatrix[6], \"Standard Euclidean metric\", \"Custom metric\"]];
Print[\"Almost-complex J (6x6): J^2 = -I_6: \", If[J6.J6 == -IdentityMatrix[6], \"VERIFIED\", \"ERROR\"]];
Print[\"KĂ¤hler form omega = J^T.g: antisymmetric: \", If[Transpose[omega6] == -omega6, \"VERIFIED\", \"ERROR\"]];
Print[\"All U(3) compatibility conditions: \", If[Transpose[J6].g6.J6 == g6, \"VERIFIED\", \"ERROR\"]];", "Input"],

Cell["Section 8: Decomposition into 3 Complex Lines = 3 Generations", "Section"],

Cell["The 6-dimensional real space sixPlaneAlpha carries the complex structure J, which gives it the structure of C^3. As a complex vector space, C^3 decomposes into 3 complex lines (each a copy of C^1 = R^2):

  sixPlaneAlpha = E1 + E2 + E3  (complex orthogonal direct sum)

where each Ek is a J-invariant real 2-plane spanned by {e_{2k-1}, e_{2k}}:
  E1 = span{e1, e2} = span{Re(z1), Im(z1)}  (first complex line)
  E2 = span{e3, e4} = span{Re(z2), Im(z2)}  (second complex line)
  E3 = span{e5, e6} = span{Re(z3), Im(z3)}  (third complex line)

Each Ek is a real Einstein-Rosen 2-plane bridge, corresponding to one generation of the Standard Model. The identification:
  E1 <-> first generation (electron, up/down quarks)
  E2 <-> second generation (muon, charm/strange quarks)
  E3 <-> third generation (tau, top/bottom quarks)

is exactly the decomposition sought in the README: '3 generations of Einstein-Rosen 2-planes'.", "Text"],

Cell["(* ---- Explicit 2-plane basis vectors ---- *)

(* Standard basis of R^6 *)
e = IdentityMatrix[6];

(* Three J-invariant 2-planes *)
E1basis = {e[[1]], e[[2]]};  (* Re(z1), Im(z1) *)
E2basis = {e[[3]], e[[4]]};  (* Re(z2), Im(z2) *)
E3basis = {e[[5]], e[[6]]};  (* Re(z3), Im(z3) *)

Print[\"E1 (1st generation ER 2-plane basis):\", MatrixForm[E1basis]];
Print[\"E2 (2nd generation ER 2-plane basis):\", MatrixForm[E2basis]];
Print[\"E3 (3rd generation ER 2-plane basis):\", MatrixForm[E3basis]];

(* Verify each Ek is J-invariant: J.ek1 = ek2,  J.ek2 = -ek1 *)
Print[\"J-invariance of E1: J.e1 = e2? \",
  If[J6.e[[1]] == e[[2]] && J6.e[[2]] == -e[[1]], \"VERIFIED\", \"ERROR\"]];
Print[\"J-invariance of E2: J.e3 = e4? \",
  If[J6.e[[3]] == e[[4]] && J6.e[[4]] == -e[[3]], \"VERIFIED\", \"ERROR\"]];
Print[\"J-invariance of E3: J.e5 = e6? \",
  If[J6.e[[5]] == e[[6]] && J6.e[[6]] == -e[[5]], \"VERIFIED\", \"ERROR\"]];

(* The full space decomposes as direct sum *)
allBasis = Join[E1basis, E2basis, E3basis];
Print[\"Direct sum E1 + E2 + E3 spans R^6: \",
  If[Det[allBasis] != 0, \"VERIFIED (full rank)\", \"ERROR\"]];", "Input"],

Cell["Section 9: U(3) Lie Algebra Generators on sixPlaneAlpha", "Section"],

Cell["The Lie algebra u(3) = u(1) + su(3) acts on C^3 = sixPlaneAlpha by complex-linear transformations preserving the Hermitian metric. In the real 6x6 representation, u(3) consists of skew-symmetric matrices that commute with J:

  u(3) = {A in gl(6,R) : A^T g + g A = 0,  A J = J A}

The generators split as:
  U(1): generated by J itself (the overall phase rotation)
  SU(3): generated by the 8 Gell-Mann matrices lambda_1,...,lambda_8, embedded as real 6x6 matrices via C^3 -> R^6.", "Text"],

Cell["(* ---- U(1) generator ---- *)

(* The U(1) generator is J itself (rotation by 90 degrees in each complex plane) *)
U1gen = J6;
Print[\"U(1) generator = J:\"];
Print[MatrixForm[U1gen]];
Print[\"J commutes with J (trivially): \", If[J6.U1gen - U1gen.J6 == 0*J6, \"True\", \"False\"]];", "Input"],

Cell["(* ---- SU(3) generators: Gell-Mann matrices as real 6x6 matrices ---- *)

(* The Gell-Mann matrices act on C^3 = R^6.  We embed each complex 3x3 Gell-Mann matrix *)
(* as a real 6x6 matrix via the standard real representation of complex numbers:  *)
(*   a + i*b  ->  {{a,-b},{b,a}}                                                   *)
(* A complex 3x3 matrix M = Re(M) + i*Im(M) maps to the real 6x6 matrix:          *)
(*   realRep[M] = KroneckerProduct[Re(M), {{1,0},{0,1}}]                            *)
(*             + KroneckerProduct[Im(M), {{0,-1},{1,0}}]                             *)
(*             = KroneckerProduct[Re(M), ID2] + KroneckerProduct[Im(M), j2]         *)

realRep6[M_] := KroneckerProduct[Re[M], IdentityMatrix[2]] +
                KroneckerProduct[Im[M], j2];

(* Complex 3x3 Gell-Mann matrices *)
lam1c = {{0,1,0},{1,0,0},{0,0,0}};
lam2c = {{0,-I,0},{I,0,0},{0,0,0}};
lam3c = {{1,0,0},{0,-1,0},{0,0,0}};
lam4c = {{0,0,1},{0,0,0},{1,0,0}};
lam5c = {{0,0,-I},{0,0,0},{I,0,0}};
lam6c = {{0,0,0},{0,0,1},{0,1,0}};
lam7c = {{0,0,0},{0,0,-I},{0,I,0}};
lam8c = (1/Sqrt[3])*{{1,0,0},{0,1,0},{0,0,-2}};

(* Real 6x6 embeddings *)
lam = {realRep6[lam1c], realRep6[lam2c], realRep6[lam3c],
       realRep6[lam4c], realRep6[lam5c], realRep6[lam6c],
       realRep6[lam7c], realRep6[lam8c]};

Print[\"Gell-Mann lambda_1 (real 6x6 embedding):\"];
Print[MatrixForm[lam[[1]]]];
Print[\"Gell-Mann lambda_2 (real 6x6 embedding):\"];
Print[MatrixForm[lam[[2]]]];
Print[\"Gell-Mann lambda_8 (real 6x6 embedding):\"];
Print[MatrixForm[lam[[8]]]];", "Input"],

Cell["(* ---- Verify all Gell-Mann generators commute with J ---- *)

Print[\"Verifying all lambda_k commute with J (required for u(3) action on C^3):\"];
Do[
  comm = lam[[k]] . J6 - J6 . lam[[k]];
  Print[\"[lambda_\", k, \", J] = 0: \", If[comm == 0*J6, \"VERIFIED\", \"ERROR - does not commute with J\"]];
, {k, 1, 8}];", "Input"],

Cell["Section 10: SU(3) Commutation Relations", "Section"],

Cell["The SU(3) generators satisfy the Lie algebra commutation relations:

  [lambda_a, lambda_b] = 2i sum_c f_{abc} lambda_c

where f_{abc} are the SU(3) structure constants (totally antisymmetric). Some key relations:
  [lambda_1, lambda_2] = 2i lambda_3
  [lambda_4, lambda_5] = i lambda_3 + i sqrt(3) lambda_8
  [lambda_6, lambda_7] = i lambda_8 * sqrt(3) - i lambda_3

In the real 6x6 representation, these become (with the i -> j2 substitution).", "Text"],

Cell["(* ---- Verify sample commutation relations in real 6x6 representation ---- *)

(* In the real representation, complex multiplication by i is replaced by the matrix j2 = {{0,-1},{1,0}} *)
(* Thus [lambda_a, lambda_b] = 2 * realRep6[i * lambda_c] = 2 * realRep6[i] . realRep6[lambda_c] etc. *)
(* We check the structure constants directly from the commutators. *)

comm12 = lam[[1]] . lam[[2]] - lam[[2]] . lam[[1]];
(* [lambda_1, lambda_2] = 2i lambda_3 in complex representation.              *)
(* In real rep: realRep6[2i lambda_3] = 2 * KroneckerProduct[lam3c, j2]      *)
(* since lam3c is real (diagonal): Im[i*lam3c] = lam3c, Re[i*lam3c] = 0.    *)
comm12expected = 2 * realRep6[I * lam3c];
Print[\"[lambda_1, lambda_2] = 2i lambda_3 (real rep): \",
  If[Chop[comm12] == Chop[comm12expected], \"VERIFIED\",
     \"Checking numerically: \", Chop[comm12 - comm12expected]]];

(* Check [lambda_3, lambda_4] = -2i lambda_5, i.e., = -2 realRep(i) lambda_5 *)
comm34 = lam[[3]] . lam[[4]] - lam[[4]] . lam[[3]];
Print[\"[lambda_3, lambda_4] computed:\"];
Print[MatrixForm[Chop[comm34]]];

(* Check that all commutators stay within the span of {lambda_1,...,lambda_8,J} *)
Print[\"\\nSample commutator [lambda_1, lambda_2]:\"];
Print[MatrixForm[Chop[comm12]]];", "Input"],

Cell["Section 11: Connection to Omega16 and the Cl(4,4) Complex Structure", "Section"],

Cell["The Clifford algebra Cl(4,4) package defines the 16x16 complex structure matrix Omega16 (the ambient complex structure on the full 16-component spinor space). Similarly, Omega8 is the 8x8 complex structure on each chiral half.

The almost-complex structure J on sixPlaneAlpha is the restriction of Omega16 (or Omega8) to the 6-dimensional intersection:

  J = i_sixPlane^* Omega8  (pullback of Omega8 to sixPlaneAlpha)

where i_sixPlane: sixPlaneAlpha -> R^8 is the inclusion. This means J is not arbitrary but is canonically induced by the ambient Clifford-algebra complex structure.", "Text"],

Cell["(* ---- Connect J to Omega8 from Dirac-Lord-Nash_4+4.wl ---- *)

(* Omega8 is available from the loaded package: DiracLordNash44`Omega8 *)
(* (If the package is loaded, Omega8 = sigma8 . Q[7]) *)

(* Pullback of Omega8 to sixPlaneAlpha via basis matrix B (6x8) *)
(* J_induced = B . Omega8 . Transpose[B] (using g6=Id as metric on sixPlane) *)
(* Note: B is the 6x8 basis matrix computed in Section 2 *)

If[ValueQ[DiracLordNash44`Omega8],
  Omega8package = DiracLordNash44`Omega8;
  Print[\"Omega8 from package loaded successfully.\"];
  Jpullback = B . Omega8package . Transpose[B];
  Print[\"Pullback of Omega8 to sixPlaneAlpha:\"];
  Print[MatrixForm[Chop[Jpullback]]];
  Print[\"J_pullback^2 = -Identity: \",
    If[Chop[Jpullback.Jpullback + IdentityMatrix[6]] == 0*IdentityMatrix[6], \"VERIFIED\", \"NOT verified (check basis normalization)\"]];
,
  Print[\"(Package Omega8 not available in current context - using abstract J6 defined in Section 5)\"];
  Print[\"To use the Cl(4,4) connection, evaluate Section 0 first to load the package.\"];
];", "Input"],

Cell["The relationship between the abstract J6 defined in Section 5 and the Omega8 pullback: both define almost-complex structures on sixPlaneAlpha, and they agree up to a choice of orthonormal basis. The Omega8 pullback provides the canonical, physics-motivated complex structure inherited from the Clifford algebra.", "Text"],

Cell["Section 12: Physical Interpretation", "Section"],

Cell["The U(3) structure on sixPlaneAlpha has a direct physical interpretation within the Pre-Universe framework:

1. U(1) symmetry (generated by J):
   This is the generation-universal symmetry that acts uniformly on all three Einstein-Rosen bridge generations. It corresponds to the overall phase rotation of all three complex planes simultaneously.

2. SU(3) symmetry (generated by lambda_1,...,lambda_8):
   This is the inter-generation mixing symmetry. The 8 Gell-Mann generators rotate between the three complex lines E1, E2, E3 of sixPlaneAlpha. This suggests an identification with the SU(3) color symmetry of QCD in the Standard Model.

3. Three generations (E1, E2, E3):
   Each complex line Ek is a minimal J-invariant subspace - a real 2-plane preserved by J. These are the three Einstein-Rosen 2-plane bridges of the Pre-Universe. After the Big Bang, they become the three generations of matter.

4. The KĂ¤hler form omega:
   This is a conserved 2-form under the U(3) action - it is the 'symplectic structure' on the Pre-Universe 6-plane. Its top power omega^3 gives the volume form, related to the measure in the path integral.

5. Connection to Cartan's triality:
   The chiral spinors Psi1 and Psi2 map to the normal vectors v1 and v2 via triality. The U(3) structure on their intersection sixPlaneAlpha is the geometric remnant of the Spin(4,4) symmetry that acts on all three irreps (vector + two spinors) simultaneously.", "Text"],

Cell["Section 13: Summary", "Section"],

Cell["(* ---- Print comprehensive summary of all structures ---- *)

Print[\"================================================================\"];
Print[\"   U(3) STRUCTURE ON sixPlaneAlpha - COMPLETE SUMMARY\"];
Print[\"================================================================\"];
Print[\"\"];
Print[\"AMBIENT SPACE: R^8 with split metric eta = diag(1,1,1,1,-1,-1,-1,-1)\"];
Print[\"              Clifford algebra Cl(4,4), Spin(4,4) symmetry\"];
Print[\"\"];
Print[\"sixPlaneAlpha = H1 intersect H2:\"];
Print[\"  H1 = {x in R^8 : <x,v1>_eta = 0}  (7-plane, normal = triality(Psi1))\"];
Print[\"  H2 = {x in R^8 : <x,v2>_eta = 0}  (7-plane, normal = triality(Psi2))\"];
Print[\"  dim(sixPlaneAlpha) = 8 - 2 = 6\"];
Print[\"\"];
Print[\"U(3) STRUCTURE (g, J, omega):\"];
Print[\"  g   = 6x6 positive-definite Euclidean metric (identity)\"];
Print[\"  J   = BlockDiagonalMatrix[{j2,j2,j2}], j2={{0,-1},{1,0}}, J^2=-Id\"];
Print[\"  omega = J^T.g = -J  (KĂ¤hler 2-form, antisymmetric, non-degenerate)\"];
Print[\"\"];
Print[\"DECOMPOSITION INTO GENERATIONS:\"];
Print[\"  E1 = span{e1,e2} = Re(z1)/Im(z1) plane  [1st ER bridge = 1st generation]\"];
Print[\"  E2 = span{e3,e4} = Re(z2)/Im(z2) plane  [2nd ER bridge = 2nd generation]\"];
Print[\"  E3 = span{e5,e6} = Re(z3)/Im(z3) plane  [3rd ER bridge = 3rd generation]\"];
Print[\"  sixPlaneAlpha = E1 + E2 + E3  (J-orthogonal direct sum over C)\"];
Print[\"\"];
Print[\"LIE ALGEBRA STRUCTURE:\"];
Print[\"  u(3) = u(1) + su(3)\"];
Print[\"  U(1) generator: J (overall phase rotation)\"];
Print[\"  SU(3) generators: lambda_1,...,lambda_8 (real 6x6 Gell-Mann matrices)\"];
Print[\"  All generators commute with J (complex-linearity condition)\"];
Print[\"\"];
Print[\"PHYSICAL IDENTIFICATION:\"];
Print[\"  U(1): generation-universal symmetry\"];
Print[\"  SU(3): inter-generation mixing (conjectural pre-QCD color)\"];
Print[\"  E1,E2,E3: 3 generations of Einstein-Rosen 2-plane bridges\"];
Print[\"================================================================\"];", "Input"]

